Okay!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Yales is the smartest anti-nuclear guy I've ever found, I was going to give him fair go at scuttling the NTR I have doodled together.  I can think of two severe issues with it as I have presented it, which are paradoxically opposites. <br>
<br>
First, the lightbulb has opacity issues, IE, it is too opaque and would be heavily stressed.<br>
<br>
Second, the reaction mass is too transparent, and it may be difficult to couple it to the radiative output effectively.  <br>
<br>
I think both of these issues can be fixed, but doing it for 60 tons per thruster could be tough....<br>
<br>
Anybody else also feel free to poke at it, and if it still looks intact after a week or so I will see about cobbling something together to float about.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
brucetrib: <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  The optimum means for disposing of a radioactive reentry body is to resolve it into fine particulate debris which will be dispersed and retained by the upper atmosphere.  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Wow!  Do you have an on-line reference to this?  If this is true, then using a gas core NTR is even safer than I thought, as for a large portion of the flight regime the default behavior in an accident is to vent the UF6 gas.  I could probably save a little mass on the fuel storage system that way, too....  <br>
