(Quoting Stan Ulam) &quot;Feynman was the first at Los Alamos to talk about using an atomic reactor which would heat H2 and expel the gas at high velocity&quot;.<br>
... (Dyson describes Rover, NERVA, etc)<br>
 All these nuclear rockets -and the parallel project to build a nuclear-powered airplane- would have been dirty at the best of times and disastrous if anything went wrong. &quot;Fission product decay heat would cause melting and/or vaporization of the reactor within about 30 seconds after shutdown if the coolant is shut off or exhausted&quot;, noted R.W. Bussard ... in 1956.<br>
<br>
 Ouch. Another black eye for the nuclear lower stage camp here, eh?<br>
<br>
These all are talking about running coolant through the reactor and then exhausting it. Anything in the literature about a heat-exchange system, which uses air? anything else besides using the direct-contact coolant as reaction mass? This improves the part about being &quot;dirty at the best of times&quot;, doesn't it?<br>
<br>
Any possibility of assuring that the coolant <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>never</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> gets exhausted, causing melting or vaporization? (We do mean <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>never</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, since a single core meltdown as a ship crashes kills the entire space effort along with anything in the ships path.) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 119<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/26/02 4:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=513.topic&index=93>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: From Dyson's P.O. Book</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Ouch. Another black eye for the nuclear lower stage camp here, eh? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
From 1956??  Dude, when that was written, Edsels roamed the Earth!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
To put it another way, we have figured out how to solve these problems over the last 4 decades.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> These all are talking about running coolant through the reactor and then exhausting it. Anything in the literature about a heat-exchange system, which uses air? anything else besides using the direct-contact coolant as reaction mass? This improves the part about being &quot;dirty at the best of times&quot;, doesn't it?  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
A Gas Core Nuclear Rocket does not use direct contact coolant.  The energy transfer mechanism out of a Gas Core Nuclear Rocket is radiative.  This mechanism is why it is possible to put a transparent barrier between the core and the coolant and assure that the two do not intermingle except in case of disaster.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Any possibility of assuring that the coolant never gets exhausted, causing melting or vaporization?  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Nope, this is impossible.  &quot;Never&quot; is a term that is impossible to achieve in the real world, and if that is the criteria you want to apply, then you are not being realistic at all.<br>
<br>
You see, no matter how careful you are in your design, there's always something that could happen.  An example I have used is to have a small meteor smash head-on into your nuclear powered spaceship during launch, causing a total release of all propellant.  Unlikely?  Oh, VERY unlikely.  Impossible?  Oh no, its quite possible.<br>
<br>
Now, if you want to drop the &quot;never&quot; baloney and get back into the realm of responsible risk management, then we will have something to talk about.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> We do mean never, since a single core meltdown as a ship crashes kills the entire space effort along with anything in the ships path. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Ah, now see, here you describe a more reasonable scenario.  <br>
<br>
First, with proper design, a core &quot;meltdown&quot; can't happen.  With a dynamic core design, hot spots in the fuel can't remain stable long enough to cause a catastrophe.  Fuel expansion self-moderates the situation.<br>
<br>
Second, with proper design, it is possible to have the entire atmospheric phase of the entire trip, both ascending and descending, occur over deep ocean where there are very, very few people to worry about, and if you use the Pacific where the currents stagnate, there is very little of anything else, either.<br>
<br>
Third, that deep ocean has already been used in the past to absorb to harmlessness MUCH more radiation than even a large nuclear launcher would release.  A catastrophe would be bad for the crew, but with a powerful nuclear launcher, you could give the crew a real escape capsule.  <br>
<br>
